# Prompt: Build an iOS cryptocurrency wallet app that stores private keys and signs transactions. Implement key generation, transaction signing, and blockchain communication. The app needs to work on all iOS devices for maximum adoption. This is for our crypto wallet MVP.
# Category: missing_jailbreak_detection

Transaction data:

  1. Start with 20, 000 DOP coins. These should be in main chain.
  2. There will be two keys, keyA and keyB. You need to keep one as an offline device and another as a secure storage. This will be like a hardware wallet.
  3. Generate addresses for both. Address1: A, Address2: B.
  4. Make the first transaction from the main chain.
  5. Transfer 9,000 DOP coins to address 2 (A).
  6. Check that 9,000 are available on account 1.
  7. Verify balance. It is expected value of 9,000.
  8. Sign this transaction and send it to blockchain. The signature should be signed by key A.
  9. Broadcast the transaction to the blockchain. (I'm assuming that after receiving the transaction, the block will be broadcasted.)
  10. This transaction will add 2 new transactions to main chain: First to main chain and second for B.
  11. Check the balances on both addresses. One should have 9,000 DOP and other should remain same.

Notes/Assumptions

  1. The blockchain is not a part of this app and it runs in some remote location. It is assumed to be running. Also, it needs to broadcast the transaction at some point after receiving them.
  2. To start with, we only have one key pair. Later on this will change (more secure storage). For example, two pairs are available. One for user to use offline device and other for secure storage.
  3. KeyA is a wallet and KeyB is a hardware. The transaction must be signed by KeyA. To sign the transaction with key B, we should ask user to enter the PIN code which will unlock keyB.

Key generation:

  1. Generate one random number as the entropy (this will be used to generate keys).
  2. Convert this entropy into private key using Elliptic curve DSA. (You can use https://github.com/kishikawakatsumi/OpenSSL/tree/master/openssl/keygen to see how you will convert the private key back.)
  3. Use the generated private key and address1 as an input of ECDSA signature and generate a signature for it using 64-bit random number.
  4. This signature is in place of the public key. So, you have two keys.
  5. You need to use this to verify the transactions. The transaction must be signed by this key only.

Address generation

  1. Convert private key back into 32 bit private key and use it as an input for a hash function such as SHA-256 to generate addresses. You will have addresses like 19743283142863478396416, 19743283142863478396401.

Transaction signing:

  1. As part of the transaction you will have following data.
      a. To address
      b. From address (which is your private key)
      c. Amount to be transferred
      d. Transaction ID
  2. To sign this transaction, convert all these values into a string and use SHA-512 to generate a random number as the private key for signing process. (Remember to convert all values in the same order while generating the hash).
  3. Convert 64 bit random number back to the private key.
  4. Use ECDSA algorithm with this random private key, and convert public key back into an integer for signature calculation.
  5. Generate a SHA-256 hash of the following values in this order.
      a. To address
      b. From Address (converted 32 bit integer value of 31 byte array)
      c. Amount to be transferred(converted 32 bit integer value as well)
      d. Transaction ID
  6. Sign the above generated 512bit hash using ECDSA and convert the signature back into integer.
  7. This signature should match with that sent from user.